{"title_page": "Spring Lake, Michigan", "text_new": "{{For|the lake with the same name in Michigan|Spring Lake (Independence Township, Michigan)}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Spring Lake, Michigan\n|settlement_type          = [[Village (United States)|Village]]\n|nickname                 = \n|motto                    =\n\n<!-- Images -->\n|image_skyline            = \n|imagesize                = \n|image_caption            = \n|image_flag               = \n|image_seal               =\n\n<!-- Maps -->\n|image_map                = Ottawa_County_Michigan_Incorporated_and_Unincorporated_areas_Spring_Lake_Highlighted.svg\n|mapsize                  = 250x200px\n|map_caption              = Location of Spring Lake, Michigan\n|image_map1               = \n|mapsize1                 = \n|map_caption1             =\n\n<!-- Location -->\n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name         = United States\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = [[Michigan]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in Michigan|County]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Ottawa County, Michigan|Ottawa]]\n\n<!-- Government -->\n|government_footnotes     = \n|government_type          = \n|leader_title             = \n|leader_name              = \n|leader_title1            = \n|leader_name1             = \n|established_title        = \n|established_date         =\n\n<!-- Area -->\n|area_footnotes           = <ref name=\"CenPopGazetteer2016\">{{cite web|title=2017 U.S. Gazetteer Files|url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/maps-data/data/gazetteer/2017_Gazetteer/2017_gaz_place_26.txt|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=Jan 3, 2019}}</ref>\n|area_magnitude           = \n|area_total_km2           = 4.96\n|area_land_km2            = 3.24\n|area_water_km2           = 1.72\n|area_total_sq_mi         = 1.91\n|area_land_sq_mi          = 1.25\n|area_water_sq_mi         = 0.67\n\n<!-- Population -->\n|population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_est           = 2493\n|pop_est_as_of            = 2018\n|population_footnotes     = <ref name =\"FactFinder\"/>\n|population_total         = 2323\n|population_density_km2   = 772.57\n|population_density_sq_mi = 2001.60\n\n<!-- General information -->\n|timezone                 = [[North American Eastern Time Zone|Eastern (EST)]]\n|utc_offset               = -5\n|timezone_DST             = EDT\n|utc_offset_DST           = -4\n|elevation_footnotes      = \n|elevation_m              = 182\n|elevation_ft             = 597\n|coordinates              = {{coord|43|4|37|N|86|11|49|W|region:US-MI_type:city_source:GNIS|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]\n|postal_code              = 49456\n|area_code                = [[Area code 616|616]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 26-75820<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=http://factfinder2.census.gov|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=American FactFinder}}</ref>\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 0638599<ref>{{gnis|0638599}}</ref>\n|website                  = http://www.springlakevillage.org/\n|footnotes                = \n|pop_est_footnotes = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/>\n|unit_pref = Imperial\n}}\n\n'''Spring Lake''' is a village in [[Ottawa County, Michigan|Ottawa County]] in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Michigan]]. The population was 2,323 at the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]]. The village is located within [[Spring Lake Township, Michigan|Spring Lake Township]].\n\n==History==\n\nIn 1837, Captain Benjamin Hopkins purchased land in the area and built a mill.  The place became known as \"Hopkins Mill\". In 1849, Thomas W. White and S.C. Hopkins recorded a [[plat]] with the name \"Mill Point\".  A post office was established with that name in May 1851. In May 1867, the post office was renamed \"Spring Lake\", which was also the name of a station on the [[Detroit, Grand Haven and Milwaukee Railway]] (later part of the [[Grand Trunk Western Railroad]]).  The Village of Spring Lake was incorporated in 1869.<ref name=\"Romig\">{{cite book | last = Romig | first = Walter | year = 1986 | title = Michigan Place Names | origyear= 1973 | publisher = Wayne State University Press | location = Detroit, Michigan | isbn = 0-8143-1838-X}}</ref> The post office continues to operate, with [[ZIP code]] 49456.\n\n==Geography==\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the village has a total area of {{convert|1.74|sqmi|sqkm|2}}, of which {{convert|1.18|sqmi|sqkm|2}} is land and {{convert|0.56|sqmi|sqkm|2}} is water.<ref name=\"Gazetteer files\">{{cite web|title=US Gazetteer files 2010|url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|access-date=2012-11-25|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120125061959/http://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt|archive-date=2012-01-25|df=}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1860= 179\n|1870= 1156\n|1880= 1372\n|1890= 1168\n|1900= 696\n|1910= 802\n|1920= 978\n|1930= 1271\n|1940= 1329\n|1950= 1824\n|1960= 2063\n|1970= 3034\n|1980= 2731\n|1990= 2537\n|2000= 2514\n|2010= 2323\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=2493\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=December 18, 2019}}</ref>\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 4, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===2010 census===\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name =\"FactFinder\">{{cite web|title=American FactFinder|url=http://factfinder2.census.gov/faces/nav/jsf/pages/index.xhtml|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2012-11-25}}</ref> of 2010, there were 2,323 people, 1,067 households, and 635 families living in the village. The [[population density]] was {{convert|1968.6|PD/sqmi|PD/km2|1}}. There were 1,301 housing units at an average density of {{convert|1102.5|/sqmi|/km2|1}}. The racial makeup of the village was 96.7% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 0.2% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.8% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 0.3% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.1% [[Race (U.S. Census)|Pacific Islander]], 0.6% from [[Race (U.S. Census)|other races]], and 1.3% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 1.8% of the population.\n\nThere were 1,067 households of which 25.8% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 48.5% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 8.3% had a female householder with no husband present, 2.7% had a male householder with no wife present, and 40.5% were non-families. 36.1% of all households were made up of individuals and 17.6% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.17 and the average family size was 2.84.\n\nThe median age in the village was 44.8 years. 21.6% of residents were under the age of 18; 6.3% were between the ages of 18 and 24; 22.5% were from 25 to 44; 29.1% were from 45 to 64; and 20.5% were 65 years of age or older. The gender makeup of the village was 47.0% male and 53.0% female.\n\n===2000 census===\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\" /> of 2000, there were 2,514 people, 1,098 households, and 666 families living in the village.  The [[population density]] was 2,372.4 per square mile (915.7/km\u00b2).  There were 1,248 housing units at an average density of 1,177.7 per square mile (454.6/km\u00b2).  The racial makeup of the village was 98.05% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 0.32% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.44% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 0.24% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.36% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 0.60% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 1.31% of the population.\n\nThere were 1,098 households out of which 25.3% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 50.5% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 7.6% had a female householder with no husband present, and 39.3% were non-families. 36.0% of all households were made up of individuals and 17.7% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.  The average household size was 2.16 and the average family size was 2.84.\n\nIn the village, the population was spread out with 20.7% under the age of 18, 5.2% from 18 to 24, 25.7% from 25 to 44, 21.9% from 45 to 64, and 26.5% who were 65 years of age or older.  The median age was 44 years. For every 100 females, there were 84.2 males.  For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 79.2 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the village was $37,889, and the median income for a family was $44,797. Males had a median income of $34,293 versus $23,986 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the village was $26,372.  About 4.6% of families and 6.1% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 6.8% of those under age 18 and 4.2% of those age 65 or over.\n\n==Notable people==\n*[[Lydia J. Newcomb Comings]] (1850\u20131946), educator, lecturer, author\n*[[Winsor McCay]], [[cartoonist]], [[animator]] known for ''[[Little Nemo in Slumberland]]'' and ''[[Gertie the Dinosaur]]\n*[[Ed Pizunski]], professional hockey player\n*[[Kate Reinders]], musical theatre actress\n*[[Jack Sprague]], [[NASCAR]] driver\n*[[Bob Wood (author)|Bob Wood]], noted author and activist\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.springlakevillage.org/ Village of Spring Lake]\n\n{{Ottawa County, Michigan}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Ottawa County, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Villages in Michigan]]\n[[Category:1849 establishments in Michigan]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1849]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the lake with the same name in Michigan|Spring Lake (Independence Township, Michigan)}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Spring Lake, Michigan\n|settlement_type          = [[Village (United States)|Village]]\n|nickname                 = \n|motto                    =\n\n<!-- Images -->\n|image_skyline            = \n|imagesize                = \n|image_caption            = \n|image_flag               = \n|image_seal               =\n\n<!-- Maps -->\n|image_map                = Ottawa_County_Michigan_Incorporated_and_Unincorporated_areas_Spring_Lake_Highlighted.svg\n|mapsize                  = 250x200px\n|map_caption              = Location of Spring Lake, Michigan\n|image_map1               = \n|mapsize1                 = \n|map_caption1             =\n\n<!-- Location -->\n|subdivision_type         = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name         = United States\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_name1        = [[Michigan]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in Michigan|County]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Ottawa County, Michigan|Ottawa]]\n\n<!-- Government -->\n|government_footnotes     = \n|government_type          = \n|leader_title             = \n|leader_name              = \n|leader_title1            = \n|leader_name1             = \n|established_title        = \n|established_date         =\n\n<!-- Area -->\n|area_footnotes           = <ref name=\"CenPopGazetteer2016\">{{cite web|title=2017 U.S. Gazetteer Files|url=https://www2.census.gov/geo/docs/maps-data/data/gazetteer/2017_Gazetteer/2017_gaz_place_26.txt|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=Jan 3, 2019}}</ref>\n|area_magnitude           = \n|area_total_km2           = 4.96\n|area_land_km2            = 3.24\n|area_water_km2           = 1.72\n|area_total_sq_mi         = 1.91\n|area_land_sq_mi          = 1.25\n|area_water_sq_mi         = 0.67\n\n<!-- Population -->\n|population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_est           = 2493\n|pop_est_as_of            = 2018\n|population_footnotes     = <ref name =\"FactFinder\"/>\n|population_total         = 2323\n|population_density_km2   = 772.57\n|population_density_sq_mi = 2001.60\n\n<!-- General information -->\n|timezone                 = [[North American Eastern Time Zone|Eastern (EST)]]\n|utc_offset               = -5\n|timezone_DST             = EDT\n|utc_offset_DST           = -4\n|elevation_footnotes      = \n|elevation_m              = 182\n|elevation_ft             = 597\n|coordinates              = {{coord|43|4|37|N|86|11|49|W|region:US-MI_type:city_source:GNIS|display=inline,title}}\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP code]]\n|postal_code              = 49456\n|area_code                = [[Area code 616|616]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 26-75820<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=http://factfinder2.census.gov|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=American FactFinder}}</ref>\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 0638599<ref>{{gnis|0638599}}</ref>\n|website                  = http://www.springlakevillage.org/\n|footnotes                = \n|pop_est_footnotes = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/>\n|unit_pref = Imperial\n}}\n\n'''Spring Lake''' is a village in [[Ottawa County, Michigan|Ottawa County]] in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Michigan]]. The population was 2,323 at the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]]. The village is located within [[Spring Lake Township, Michigan|Spring Lake Township]].\n\n==History==\n\nIn 1837, Captain Benjamin Hopkins purchased land in the area and built a mill.  The place became known as \"Hopkins Mill\". In 1849, Thomas W. White and S.C. Hopkins recorded a [[plat]] with the name \"Mill Point\".  A post office was established with that name in May 1851. In May 1867, the post office was renamed \"Spring Lake\", which was also the name of a station on the [[Detroit, Grand Haven and Milwaukee Railway]] (later part of the [[Grand Trunk Western Railroad]]).  The Village of Spring Lake was incorporated in 1869.<ref name=\"Romig\">{{cite book | last = Romig | first = Walter | year = 1986 | title = Michigan Place Names | origyear= 1973 | publisher = Wayne State University Press | location = Detroit, Michigan | isbn = 0-8143-1838-X}}</ref> The post office continues to operate, with [[ZIP code]] 49456.\n\n==Geography==\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], the village has a total area of {{convert|1.74|sqmi|sqkm|2}}, of which {{convert|1.18|sqmi|sqkm|2}} is land and {{convert|0.56|sqmi|sqkm|2}} is water.<ref name=\"Gazetteer files\">{{cite web|title=US Gazetteer files 2010|url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|access-date=2012-11-25|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120125061959/http://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/files/Gaz_places_national.txt|archive-date=2012-01-25|df=}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1860= 179\n|1870= 1156\n|1880= 1372\n|1890= 1168\n|1900= 696\n|1910= 802\n|1920= 978\n|1930= 1271\n|1940= 1329\n|1950= 1824\n|1960= 2063\n|1970= 3034\n|1980= 2731\n|1990= 2537\n|2000= 2514\n|2010= 2323\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=2493\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=December 18, 2019}}</ref>\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 4, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n\n===2010 census===\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name =\"FactFinder\">{{cite web|title=American FactFinder|url=http://factfinder2.census.gov/faces/nav/jsf/pages/index.xhtml|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2012-11-25}}</ref> of 2010, there were 2,323 people, 1,067 households, and 635 families living in the village. The [[population density]] was {{convert|1968.6|PD/sqmi|PD/km2|1}}. There were 1,301 housing units at an average density of {{convert|1102.5|/sqmi|/km2|1}}. The racial makeup of the village was 96.7% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 0.2% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.8% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 0.3% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.1% [[Race (U.S. Census)|Pacific Islander]], 0.6% from [[Race (U.S. Census)|other races]], and 1.3% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 1.8% of the population.\n\nThere were 1,067 households of which 25.8% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 48.5% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 8.3% had a female householder with no husband present, 2.7% had a male householder with no wife present, and 40.5% were non-families. 36.1% of all households were made up of individuals and 17.6% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.17 and the average family size was 2.84.\n\nThe median age in the village was 44.8 years. 21.6% of residents were under the age of 18; 6.3% were between the ages of 18 and 24; 22.5% were from 25 to 44; 29.1% were from 45 to 64; and 20.5% were 65 years of age or older. The gender makeup of the village was 47.0% male and 53.0% female.\n\n===2000 census===\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR2\" /> of 2000, there were 2,514 people, 1,098 households, and 666 families living in the village.  The [[population density]] was 2,372.4 per square mile (915.7/km\u00b2).  There were 1,248 housing units at an average density of 1,177.7 per square mile (454.6/km\u00b2).  The racial makeup of the village was 98.05% [[White (U.S. Census)|White]], 0.32% [[African American (U.S. Census)|African American]], 0.44% [[Native American (U.S. Census)|Native American]], 0.24% [[Asian (U.S. Census)|Asian]], 0.36% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 0.60% from two or more races. [[Hispanic (U.S. Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Latino (U.S. Census)|Latino]] of any race were 1.31% of the population.\n\nThere were 1,098 households out of which 25.3% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 50.5% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 7.6% had a female householder with no husband present, and 39.3% were non-families. 36.0% of all households were made up of individuals and 17.7% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.  The average household size was 2.16 and the average family size was 2.84.\n\nIn the village, the population was spread out with 20.7% under the age of 18, 5.2% from 18 to 24, 25.7% from 25 to 44, 21.9% from 45 to 64, and 26.5% who were 65 years of age or older.  The median age was 44 years. For every 100 females, there were 84.2 males.  For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 79.2 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the village was $37,889, and the median income for a family was $44,797. Males had a median income of $34,293 versus $23,986 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the village was $26,372.  About 4.6% of families and 6.1% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 6.8% of those under age 18 and 4.2% of those age 65 or over.\n\n==Notable people==\n*[[Lydia J. Newcomb Comings]] (1850\u20131946), educator, lecturer, author\n*[[Winsor McCay]], [[cartoonist]], [[animator]] known for ''[[Little Nemo in Slumberland]]'' and ''[[Gertie the Dinosaur]]\n*[[Ed Pizunski]], professional hockey player\n*[[Kate Reinders]], musical theatre actress\n*[[Jack Sprague]], [[NASCAR]] driver\n*[[Bob Wood (author)|Bob Wood]], noted author and activist\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.springlakevillage.org/ Village of Spring Lake]\n*[http://www.michiganrailroads.com/RRHX/Stations/CountyStations/OttawaStations/SpringLakeMI.htm Photo of railway station]\n\n{{Ottawa County, Michigan}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Ottawa County, Michigan]]\n[[Category:Villages in Michigan]]\n[[Category:1849 establishments in Michigan]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1849]]\n", "name_user": "Deusexmechanicus", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:removed broken link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spring_Lake,_Michigan"}
{"title_page": "Rob Redding", "text_new": "{{Infobox writer\n| name         = Robert \"Rob\" Redding Jr.\n| image        = Rob Redding.jpg\n| imagesize    = \n| caption      = \n| pseudonym    = Rob Redding\n| birth_name   = Robert Redding, Jr.\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1976|01|13}}\n| birth_place  = [[Atlanta]] [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], U.S.\n| death_date   = \n| death_place  =  \n| genre        = Media, music and art\n| subject      = \n| movement     = Independent\n| notableworks = Redding News Review, Author of Why Black Lives Matter, Not a Nonviolent Negro, Disrupter, Where's the Change?, Resurrection and Resolution of Risk\n| occupation   = \n*Chairman and CEO of Redding Communications, Inc.\n*Editor, Publisher and Host of ''[[Redding News Review]]'' \n| years_active = 1994\u2013present \n| alma_mater   = [[Marshall University]] and [[University of Louisiana at Monroe|University of Louisiana]]\n| spouse       = LaWanda Hunt (1999 to 2005, div.)\n| partner      = \n| children     = Rachel Redding (stepdaughter)\n| awards       = 100 Most Important Talk Show Hosts in America, Associated Press award, gold ADDY award\n| website      = \n}}\n'''Robert \"Rob\" Redding, Jr.''' (born January 13, 1976) is an American [[artist]]. His practice spans a broad range of media including sound, performance, [[Conceptual art|conceptual]], language and visual. He is a [[professor]], [[media proprietor]], award-winning [[radio host|radio talk show host]], bestselling [[author]] and [[Independent (voter)|independent]] [[journalist]].<ref name=\"Urbaninsight\">{{cite web |work=Urbaninsight|url=https://www.urbaninsite.com/news/rob-redding-next-thursday/ |title=Biography |accessdate=}}</ref> Redding is known as the founder and [[publisher]] of ''[[Redding News Review]]'' and host of a [[talk radio]] show and [[podcast]]. In 2003, he was among few blacks to be named to Talkers Magazine's \"100 Most Important Radio Talk Show Hosts in America\" and has received a proclamation for his work by the Atlanta City Council the same year.<ref name=\"RNR returns to Atlanta\">{{cite web |work=Redding News Review back in ATL |url=http://www.radiofacts.com/rob-redding-returns-to-waok-in-atlanta/ |title=Biography |accessdate=}}</ref> He made history being the only black program director in white-dominated talk radio station in 2009.<ref name=\"Rob Redding PD\">{{cite web |work=Rob Redding PD |url=http://www.allaccess.com/news-talk-sports/10-questions/archive/4766/10-questions-with-robert-rob-redding-jr |title=10 Questions |accessdate=}}</ref> His web site [[Redding News Review]] has earned three consecutive Black Web Awards.<ref name=\"RNR BWA\">{{cite web |work=Redding News Review BWA |url=http://www2.cincinnati.com/blogs/tv/2011/11/08/rob-redding-show-coming-to-wdbz-am/ |title=Biography |accessdate=}}</ref> He currently runs the web's oldest black news aggregation outlet and first and most successful stand-alone subscriber-based web site and talk show.<ref name=\"RNR sub\">{{cite web |work=Redding News Review Sub |url=http://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/128398/redding-news-review-moves-to-subscription-model |title=Biography |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nRedding is the son of Rev. Robert Redding Sr., a former  Atlanta pastor and former president of the Fayette County's Black Voters League, and the late Mary Ann Redding, who was an Atlanta public school teacher and a Fayette school board candidate.<ref name=\"Redding Artist Statement\">{{cite web |work=Redding News Review |url=http://reddingnewsreview.com/smearsite/robert_redding_jr_art_resume.htm |title=Biography |accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref>\n\nHe gained his artistic ability from his mother Mary - who was part eastern European [[Jewish]], black, white, Native American and Asian - and his abilities to communicate effectively from his mother and father - who is part black and white.<ref name=\"Gay Letter\">{{cite web |work=Out Loud|url=http://gayletter.com/event/rob-redding-on-race-losing-his-boyfriend-to-gun-violence |title=Out Loud Biography }}</ref> And credits his oldest sister Keena for taking him to many of his early art shows and childhood teacher for her influence.<ref name=\"Smear Painting Bio\">{{cite web |work=Smear Painting|url=http://smearpainting.com/robertreddingsite/biography.html |title=Biography |accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref>\n\nHis formal training is in [[Broadcast media|media]]. He graduated from [[Marshall University]] in [[West Virginia]] with a Master's in Communication and is known for his work in sound.<ref name=\"RNR\">{{cite web |work=Redding News Review |url=http://reddingnewsreview.com/robertreddingsite/biography.html |title=Biography |accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Sound==\nHe began his [[performative]] [[Broadcast media|media]] career as a hip-hop radio personality at KZWA-FM, while at [[McNeese State University]] in Lake Charles in 1994.<ref name=\"RNR\">{{cite web |work=Redding News Review |url=http://reddingnewsreview.com/robertreddingsite/biography.html |title=Biography |accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 1996, he accepted a full-time position as a hip-hop night personality at [[WIBB-FM]] in [[Macon, GA]], where he was named \"Tony Smoove\" by his program director. Macon was also the home of another Redding family member, '60s soul singer [[Otis Redding]].<ref name=\"RNR\"/>\n\nHe left hip-hop for talk radio and journalism, working at a series of newspapers: ''The Prince George's Sentinel'', ''The Prince George's Gazette'', ''The Prince George's Journal'', ''The Macon Telegraph'', and finally ''[[The Washington Times]]''. During that same time he began his talk radio career filling in for Bernie McCain on Radio-One's [[WOL (AM)|WOL]] in Washington, D.C. in 1999. In 2001, he landed his first full-time job in talk radio doing afternoons at CBS Radio's [[WAOK]]-AM, where he started ReddingNewsReview.com. He left the station in 2003 and began syndicating his talk radio show while filling in for [[Ambrose I. Lane Sr.]] on SiriusXM 128 [[The Power (XM)|The Power]].<ref name=\"RNR\"/>\n\nHe later inked his own weekend syndication deals with GCN and Sirius XM in 2008, while finishing his undergraduate studies at the University of Louisiana-Monroe.<ref name=\"XM\">{{cite press release |url=http://xmradio.mediaroom.com/index.php?s=press_releases&item=1600 |publisher=XM Radio |title=Press Release}}</ref><ref name=\"ULM\">{{cite press release |url=http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:SbIogUsUuCsJ:www.ulm.edu/alumni/goodnews/july2009/alumni_news.html+&cd=7&hl=en&ct=clnk&gl=us |publisher=ULM |title=Press Release}}</ref>\n\nOn August 30, 2010, he began doing a weekday show for GCN, while still doing the Sunday show. The weekday show aired in multiple markets and at one time on Sirius XM daily from April 2012 to February 2013. The Sirius XM deal ended after nearly half a decade and more than 420 episodes on Feb. 10, 2013.<ref name=\"Radio Online\">{{cite news |work=Radio Online |title=Rob Redding Launches Syndicated Weekday Show |url=http://news.radio-online.com/cgi-bin/rol.exe/headline_id=n21094 |date=August 19, 2010 |accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"prnewswire\">{{cite news |work=Radio Online |title=SiriusXM Launches \"The B. Smith and 'Thank You Dan' Show\"}}</ref>\n\nRedding moved to Brussels Belgium in 2013. Living in [[Brussels]] communities of [[Saint-Gilles, Belgium]] and then [[Schaerbeek]], he became first to broadcast his afternoon talk show via GCN to American audiences nightly from Europe.<ref name=\"AA\">{{cite web |work=AA |url=http://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/121530/redding-news-review-now-airing-from-brussels |title=news |accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref>\n\nRedding made talk history when he made his program the first ever and most successful stand-alone spoken word program available exclusively to subscribers on his subscriber-supported Web site, at the conclusion of the GCN deal on April 1, 2014.<ref name=\"AA2\">{{cite web |work=AA2 |url=http://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/128398/redding-news-review-moves-to-subscription-model |title=news |accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref> The program celebrated its 1000 episode in June 2018.<ref name=\"Redding 1000\">{{cite web |work=RNR10002 |url=https://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/177266 | title='Redding News Review Unrestricted' Reaches 1,000-Episode Milestone}}</ref><ref name=\"Redding celebrates 1000\">{{cite web |url=http://www.urbaninsite.com/news/rob-redding-celebrates-episode-1000-episode/ | title=Rob Redding Celebrates Episode 1000}}</ref><ref name=\"\u2018Redding Milestone\">{{cite web |work=RNR10004 |url=https://radiofacts.com/redding-news-review-unrestriced/?singlepage=1 | title='Redding News Review Unrestricted' Reaches 1,000-Episode Milestone}}</ref> Radio online said that the show has an \"impressive base\" of nearly half the country listening as it completed its 1000 show.<ref name=\"Episode 1000\">{{cite web |work=Episode 1000 |url=https://news.radio-online.com/cgi-bin/rol.exe/headline_id=n35565 |title=Redding News Review Unrestricted' Reaches 1000th Episode}}</ref>\n\nRedding has also used numerous conceptual elements of sound in his talk shows and inserted his performance into popular culture through music.\n\n* \u201cNot a Nonviolent Negro\u201d(Amazon/CD Baby/Crystal Castle, 2013) \nOn March 5, 2013, he released a [[performative]] [[dance]] [[album]] entitled \"Not a Nonviolent Negro\" on iTunes and Amazon.com via CD Baby. The album, which takes [[sound]] of himself, callers and clips of his talk show and sets them to heavy dance beats, reached No. 1 on Amazon.com. The album is considered a soundtrack to his No. 1 best-selling book \"Not a Nonviolent Negro: How I Survived Obama.\" The book and album were released on the same day.<ref name=\"'Not a Nonviolent Negro' album, book No. 1 in multiple categories\" />\n\n* \u201cUnleash the Whip\u201d(Amazon/CD Baby/Crystal Castle, 2012) \nOn Dec. 4, 2012, he released a performative dance album entitled \"Unleash the Whip!\" on iTunes and Amazon.com via CD Baby. The album, which also takes portions of his talk show and sets them to heavy dance beats, reached No. 2 on Amazon.com and got 3 1/2 stars from former About.com dance music critic Jimi Bruce.<ref name=\"Unleash the Whip! No. 2 on Amazon.com; Gets 3 1/2 stars from About.com's former critic\">{{cite web |title=Unleash the Whip! No. 2 on Amazon.com; Gets 3 1/2 stars from About.com's former critic|url=http://www.reddingnewsreview.com/newspages/2012newspages/unleash_no35_amazon_12_1000121.htm/|accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref>\n\n* \u201cTony Smoove's Aircheck Vol. 1\u201d(Crystal Castle, 1998) \nUnleash the Whip! was his second album. His first album, published under DJ Tony Smoove, did not chart but was the first recording of rapper Bubba Sparxx.<ref name=\"WAOK\u2019s Rob Redding tries his hand in dance music: \u2018Unleash the Whip\u2019\">{{cite web |title=WAOK's Rob Redding tries his hand in dance music: 'Unleash the Whip'|url=http://blogs.ajc.com/radio-tv-talk/2012/10/27/waoks-rob-redding-tries-his-hand-ini-dance-music-unleash-the-whip/|accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=2 style=\"width:13em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=2 style=\"width:13em;\"| Album details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=10| Peak chart positions\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Amazon.com]]<br><ref name=uk>{{cite web|url=http://www.reddingnewsreview.com/newspages/2012newspages/unleash_no35_amazon_12_1000121.htm |title=Amazon.com Charts > Rob Redding|publisher=Redding NewsReview.com|work=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=2012-12-21}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Not a Nonviolent Negro''\n|\n* Released: 5 March 2013\n* Label: Crystal Castle\n* Formats: [[Music download|digital download]]\n| 1 || 1 |\n|-\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Unleash the Whip!''\n|\n* Released: 4 December 2012\n* Label: Crystal Castle\n* Formats: [[Music download|digital download]]\n| 2 || 2 |\n|-\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Tony Smoove's Aircheck Volume 1''\n|\n* Released: 1998\n* Label: Crystal Castle/Rude Records\n* Format: [[Compact Disc|CD]]\n| - || - |\n|-\n|}\n\n==Language Arts and Sound ==\nRedding's Web site and talk show, which are both called ''[[Redding News Review]]'', are avant-garde creations.<ref name=\"AllAccess\">{{cite web |url=http://www.allaccess.com/news-talk-sports/10-questions/archive/4766-10-questions-with-robert-rob-redding-jr |title=10 questions with.... Robert \"Rob\" Redding Jr. |work=Redding News Review |accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref> The Web site has been called the \"vanguard of Internet news sites\" by AllAccess.com.<ref name=\"AllAccess\">{{cite web |url=http://www.allaccess.com/news-talk-sports/10-questions/archive/4766-10-questions-with-robert-rob-redding-jr |title=10 questions with.... Robert \"Rob\" Redding Jr. |work=Redding News Review |accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref> The Web site has been called \"an Internet clearinghouse for African-American news,\" by The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.<ref name=\"AJC\"/>\n\nThe Web site - which is the first subscriber supported and oldest black news aggregation portal - stories are syndicated hourly by Google News. Its stories have been heard regularly on [[NPR]] and the [[Fox News Channel]]. Its comprehensive coverage of the black community became a resource for Fox News during the [[Don Imus]]' [[Don Imus#Rutgers women's basketball controversy|\"nappy-headed ho's\" controversy]]. Its scoops have also been acknowledged or linked to by [[Black Entertainment Television|BET]], [[MSNBC]], ''[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]'', ''[[Roll Call]]'', ''[[The Baltimore Sun]]'', ''[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]'', ''[[The Washington Post]]'',''[[The Washington Times]]'', and The [[National Newspaper Association]].<ref name=\"reddingnews\"/>\n\nRedding News Review exposed former Atlanta Mayor and United Nations Ambassador [[Andrew Young]]'s comments about Sen. [[Barack Obama]] not being ready to be president.<ref name=\"AJC\">{{cite news |first=Jim |last=Galloway |work=Political Insider |publisher=[[Atlanta Journal-Constitution]] |title=On how Andy Young\u2019s comments on Obama came to light |url=http://www.ajc.com/metro/content/shared-blogs/ajc/politicalinsider/entries/2007/12/10/more_on_those_obama_comments_b.html |date=December 10, 2007 |accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe Web site exposed that syndicated columnist [[Leonard Pitts]] was being threatened by a white supremacist group.<ref name=\"reddingnews\">{{cite web |url=http://reddingnewsreview.com/ourstory.htm |title=Our Story |work=Redding News Review |accessdate=November 18, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111027231808/http://reddingnewsreview.com/ourstory.htm |archivedate=October 27, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nThe Web site exposed NBC Nightly News Managing Editor and Anchor [[Brian Williams]] comments about diversity not being a big issue. Both Williams and NBC apologized for those comments.<ref name=\"reddingnews\"/>\n\nOn the radio talk show Redding, who refers to himself as \"America's Independent Voice\", has been called \"The voice of the voiceless\" and \"the prophet of rage\" by his listeners.<ref name=\"reddingnews\"/>\n\nRedding News Review has been the most listened to black independent talk show host in the United States of America&nbsp;\u2013 heard six days a week for nearly half decade and more than 420 episodes in all 50 states via Sirius XM Satellite Radio and on numerous radio stations for more than 6 years and 3,600 hours via his former network deal with Genesis Communications Network.<ref name=\"reddingnews\"/><ref name=\"radiofacts2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.radiofacts.com/rob-redding-returns-to-waok-in-atlanta/ |title=Rob Redding Returns to WAOK in Atlanta |work=Radio Facts |accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe Redding New Review radio show host Rob Redding was named one of the \"100 most important radio talk show hosts in America\" by industry trade ''Talkers'' magazine.<ref name=\"radiofacts2\"/>\n\nHe has also been called a \"rising star\" (''[[Talkers magazine]]''), \"one of the most respected names in the media\" (''[[Upscale magazine]]''), \"one of the most intellectual and intriguing radio talk show hosts since [[Tavis Smiley]]\" (''[[Radio Facts]]''). The same publication later wrote he is \u201cincredibly intelligent and talented radio talk show host\u2026he is a rolling stone who is not afraid to tackle some of the \u2018uncomfortable\u2019 issues in the black community.\" <ref name=\"Radio Facts 2017\">{{cite web |url=https://radiofacts.com/rob-redding-confronts-caller-about-black-homophobia/ |title=Rob Redding Confronts Caller about Black Homophobia |work=Radio Facts |accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref> He was awarded a proclamation by the [[Atlanta, Georgia#Government|Atlanta City Council]] for his hard hitting uniquely Independent [[talk radio]] show.<ref name=\"GCN\"/>\n\nOn April 1, 2014, Redding's talk show morphed into \"Redding News Review Unrestricted\" becoming the first ever and most successful stand-alone spoken word program available exclusively on a Web site - via ReddingNewsReview.com<ref name=\"GCN\">{{Cite web | url=http://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/128398/redding-news-review-moves-to-subscription-model | title=Redding News Review Moves to Subscription Model}}</ref>\nJust four years later, the program celebrated its 1000 episode in June 2018.<ref name=\"Redding 1000\">{{cite web |work=RNR10002 |url=https://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/177266 | title='Redding News Review Unrestricted' Reaches 1,000-Episode Milestone}}</ref><ref name=\"Redding celebrates 1000\">{{cite web |url=http://www.urbaninsite.com/news/rob-redding-celebrates-episode-1000-episode/ | title=Rob Redding Celebrates Episode 1000}}</ref><ref name=\"\u2018Redding Milestone\">{{cite web |work=RNR10004 |url=https://radiofacts.com/redding-news-review-unrestriced/?singlepage=1 | title='Redding News Review Unrestricted' Reaches 1,000-Episode Milestone}}</ref> Radio online said that the show has an \"impressive base\" of nearly half the country listening as it completed its 1000 show.<ref name=\"Episode 1000\">{{cite web |work=Episode 1000 |url=https://news.radio-online.com/cgi-bin/rol.exe/headline_id=n35565 |title=Redding News Review Unrestricted' Reaches 1000th Episode}}</ref> Castropolis said Redding's show is \"one of the most important Black Voices in America today.\" <ref name=\"Castropolis Instagram\">{{cite web |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B4YF_Vgp-8W/ |title=Rob Redding on Instagram |work=Insta |accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to being on the air nationwide, he was once one of the only black program directors of a mainstream conservative [[talk radio]] station, [[KMLB]]-AM in [[Monroe, Louisiana]].<ref name=\"Radio Ink\">https://docs.google.com/gview?a=v&q=cache%3A9mM2cMXpkkAJ%3Awww.reddingnewsreview.com%2Fpdfs%2FRI_p13_Redding_10-19_p37.PDF+kmlb+redding&hl=en&gl=us&sig=AFQjCNFPJ8xj4bI6LwZhdrxq9TqEbeqLnw&pli=1 Rob Redding, KMLB</ref>\n\n==Best-Selling Language Arts Publications==\nIn language arts, Redding is author of nine consecutive best-selling [[books]] and an e-guide.\n\n* \u201cThe Professor\u201d(Amazon, 2019)\nRedding's most recent book, \"The Professor: Witnessing White Power\" released on May 1 uses empiricism to explore how interracial gay encounters may have influenced black leadership. The book details the sex lives of [[Jean-Michel Basquiat]], [[James Baldwin]], [[Marvin Gaye]], [[Richard Pryor]] and [[Malcolm X]]. It contains new information about Basquiat\u2019s relationship with Klaus Nomi. Radio Facts called the book \"hard hitting\", \"controversial\" and \"explosive.\" The book debuted at No. 1 on Amazon's \u201cNew Releases in LGBT Literary Criticism\u201d and \u201cNew Releases in Gay & Lesbian Literary Criticism.\u201d <ref name=\"Radio Facts\">{{cite web |publisher=www.radiofacts.com|title=Rob Redding\u2019s book \u2018The Professor\u2019 hits No. 1|url= https://radiofacts.com/rob-reddings-book-the-professor-hits-no-1/}}</ref> The book is his most successful since 2013 \"Not a Nonviolent Negro.\"\n\n* \u201cOut Loud\u201d(Amazon, 2017) \nRedding's Out Loud was his tell-all performance and conceptual autobiography. The [[performative]] Brook - half audio/broadcast and half book - was released on Oct. 13, 2017 exclusively to his talk show subscribers and to the entire nation on Nov. 6th. The Brook has debuted at No. 2 on \"Amazon.com Hot New Releases Gay and Lesbian Biographies and Memoirs.\"  The book matched his most successful books Sinister Citizen and Not a Nonviolent Negro by being ranked in the Top 100 for five straight weeks. The book has been called \"shocking\" by CBS.<ref name=\"CBS\">{{cite web |publisher=www.atlanta.cbslocal.com|title=Black Independent Radio Host Releases Tell All Book That Reveals His Alternative Lifestyle|url= http://atlanta.cbslocal.com/2017/11/24/black-conservative-radio-host-reveals-he-sleeps-with-white-men/|date=2017-11-24}}</ref> The NYC GAYLETTER called the book \"juicy\" just after Redding pulled it from Amazon in January 2018 and making it only available for a short time on his website ReddingNewsReview.com <ref name=\"GayLetter\">{{cite web |publisher=www.gayletter.com|title=Rob Redding|url= http://gayletter.com/event/rob-redding-on-race-losing-his-boyfriend-to-gun-violence/}}</ref><ref name=\"Amazon Image\">{{cite web |publisher=www.Amazon.net|title=Amazon|url= http://reddingnewsreview.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/no2.jpg}}</ref>\n\n* \u201cSinister Citizen\u201d(Amazon, 2017) \nRedding's book, \"Sinister Citizen\" is his first fiction book ever. The book, which deals with President Trump's America, has been called \"fascinating\" by KKXX. The book has reached the Top 30 on \"Amazon.com Hot New Releases LGBT Short Reads\" and was in the Top 50 in pre-orders on the same list.<ref name=\"KKXX intv\">{{cite web |publisher=www.kkxx.net|title=KKXX intv|url= http://www.kkxx.net/all-podcasts/LocalTalk/2017_03_17_Jerry-Olenyn-Sinister-Citizen-Rob-Redding.mp3}}</ref>\n\n* ''Why Black Lives Matter: How Borigination explains how to get police and whites to treat blacks like people'' (Amazon, 2015)\nRedding's conceptual book, ''Why Black Lives Matter: How Borigination explains how to get police and whites to treat blacks like people'' was officially released on July 6, 2015, but peaked at the top of multiple charts on Amazon.com two days ahead that when it was exclusively released to subscribers of his talk show and website on July 3. The book surged to No. 1 on Amazon.com \"Hot New Releases\" in \"Philosophy and Reference\" and \"Philosophy and Criticism\" categories and rose to No. 2  in \"Philosophy and Criticism\" and \"No. 3 in \"Philosophy and Reference\" respectively among Amazon.com's Best Sellers lists. This was also the first time Redding has topped the Amazon.com \"Hot New Releases\" in \"Philosophy and Reference\" list since his 2012 release of his book \"Disrupter.\" The foreword was pinned by Dr. Lewis R. Gordon, who also wrote a foreword for Redding's book \"Resurrection.\" <ref name=\"Radio Vet \">{{cite web |publisher=radiofacts.com|title=Radio Vet Talk Show Host Rob Redding Writes Another Best-Selling Amazon E-Book \"Why Black Lives in Matter\u2026\"|url=http://www.radiofacts.com/radio-vet-talk-show-host-rob-redding-writes-another-best-selling-amazon-e-book-why-black-lives-in-matter/}}</ref><ref name=\"Rob Redding Bio\">{{cite web |publisher=RobRedding.com|title=Rob Redding's Book A Top Seller|url=http://www.reddingnewsreview.com/robertreddingsite/biography.html}}</ref>\n\n* \u201cUnthinkable: Poems, Philosophies and Paintings\u201d(Amazon, 2014) \nRedding's conceptual \"Unthinkable: Poems, Philosophies and Paintings\", released on July 7, 2014, was finished while he lived in [[Brussels]] after more than 20 years of writing and painting. \"Unthinkable\" peaked on July 13, 2014 on Amazon \"Hot New Releases\" at \"No. 4\" in \"Art and Painting\" and \"No. 7\" in \"Reference and Quotations.\" It also ranked \"No. 27\" in \"Art and Painting\" and \"No. 47\" in \"Reference and Quotations\" respectively on Amazon.com's Best Sellers lists.The book was provided for free to subscribers of Redding's talk show and website.<ref name=\"Rob Redding\u2019s Book A Top Seller\">{{cite web |publisher=UrbanInsite|title=Rob Redding's Book A Top Seller|url=http://www.urbaninsite.com/?p=34461}}</ref>\n\n* \u201cNot a Nonviolent Negro: How I Survived Obama\u201d(Amazon, 2013) \nRedding's most successful conceptual book, \"Not a Nonviolent Negro: How I Survived Obama\" debuted at No. 1 on Amazon.com in three categories on March 6, 2013. The book, which was released on March 5, was on No. 1 \"Best Sellers List\" in \"Nationalism\" and \"Hot New Releases\" in the \"Social Philosophy\" and \"Nationalism\" categories respectfully. He says it is his most successful book to date. The book also has a soundtrack \"Not a Nonviolent Negro\" which also went to No. 1 on Amazon.com.<ref name=\"'Not a Nonviolent Negro' album, book No. 1 in multiple categories\">{{cite web |publisher=CBS|title=Disrupter|url=http://www.reddingnewsreview.com/newspages/2013newspages/not_a_nonviolent_negro_13_10000023.htm}}</ref>\n\n* \u201cDisrupter: Pathway to Political Independence\u201d(Amazon, 2012) \nHis second best-selling conceptual and [[performance]] book was \"Disrupter: Pathway to Political Independence\". Disrupter debuted at No. 1 on Amazon.com \"Hot New Releases\" - \"Political Reference\" list on Aug. 13 2012 and remained there for more than a week. The book is considered a reference guide for independents and includes parts of Redding's life story.<ref name=\"Disrupter\">{{cite web |publisher=CBS|title=Disrupter|url=http://atlanta.cbslocal.com/2012/08/14/redding-book-debuts-at-1-on-amazon/|accessdate=August 15, 2011}}</ref>\n\n* \u201cResurrection: A Historical Anthology of two Forgotten African-American Philosophers\u201d(Amazon, 2012) \nHis third best-selling book was \"Resurrection: A Historical Anthology of two Forgotten African-American Philosophers.\" The e-book, which was released on April 4, 2012, reached No. 3 on the Amazon.com list of \"Hot New Releases\" in less than a week.<ref name=\"Resurrection\">{{cite web |publisher=Resurrection|title=Resurrection|url=http://www.urbanradionation.com/2012/04/talk-show-host-rob-reddings-new-book-on.html|accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref>\n\n* \u201cWhere's the Change?: Why Neither Obama, nor the GOP Can Solve America\u2019s Problems\u201d(Amazon, 2012)\nRedding's conceptual e-book \"Where's the Change?: Why Neither Obama, nor the GOP Can Solve America\u2019s Problems'', which was released on Jan. 13, 2012, reached the top 50 on Amazon.com. The book quickly has been as high as No. 30 on Amazon's Top 100 books. Redding is also author of ''Hired Hatred: Why politicians and the political prejudices they tout are mutually exclusive from good government''. His Independent [[manifesto]] is said to \"invoke an activist spirit,\" according to a review in 2005 by New York's ''Black Star News''.<ref name=\"Where's the Change?\">{{cite web |publisher=Where's the Change?|title=Where's the Change|url=http://atlanta.cbslocal.com/2012/02/01/wheres-the-change-hits-top-50-on-amazon-com|accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref>\n\n* \u201cOne a Day Fade Away\u201d(Amazon, 2012)\nHe is also the author of the \u201cOne a Day Fade Away\u201d diet e-guide, which was ranked as high as No. 29 on the \u201cAmazon Best Sellers\u201d listing in April 2012. The guide has been out since 2011 and was his third best-seller in less than 90 days.<ref name=\"One a Day Fade Away\">{{cite web |publisher=One a Day Fade Away|title=One a Day Fade Away |url=http://urbanradionation.wordpress.com/2012/04/27/rob-redding-has-third-best-selling-book-in-90-days}}</ref>\n\n==Academic Language Arts Publications==\n* \u201cBlack Voices, White Power: Members of the black press make meaning of media hegemony\u201d(Journal of Black Studies, 2017) \nIn winter of 2015, he wrote his [[thesis]] \u201cBlack Voices, White Power: Members of the black press make meaning of media hegemony\u201d to satisfy his Master's in [[Communication Studies]] degree while teaching at [[Marshall University]]. He said that the thesis \"gives an on the record voice to black employees who toil at white-owned black-focused media about their experiences as it relates to content decisions and beyond.\u201d The thesis was published in the Journal of Black Studies in March 2017.<ref name=\"Rob Redding JOBS\">{{cite journal |title=Rob Redding thesis |journal=Journal of Black Studies |volume = 48|issue=2 |pages=143\u2013164 |doi=10.1177/0021934716681152 |year=2017 |last1=Redding |first1=Robert }}</ref><ref name=\"Rob Redding Masters\">{{cite web |publisher=Redding News Review|title=Rob Redding Responds To \"You Tell Us\" Urban Radio The Future|url=http://www.urbaninsite.com/voice/insite/rob-redding-responds-to-you-tell-us-urban-radio-the-future/ |accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref>\n\n* \u201cResolution of Risk\u201d(The Journal of the International Public Debate Association, 2009)\nRedding is also author of the \"Resolution of Risk,\" which was first used at the International Public Debate Association's National Tournament after being published in the organization's peer-reviewed publication, \"The Journal of the International Public Debate Association,\" and being presented by Redding before a packed audience.<ref name=\"Resolution of Risk\">{{cite press release |first=Laura |last=Harris |publisher=[[University of Louisiana at Monroe]], Office of Public Information |title=Redding's article published in peer-reviewed journal |url=http://www.ulm.edu/universityrelations/news/apr09/redding.html |date=April 16, 2009 |accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Visual and Conceptual Art==\nRedding is an [[artist]], who paints [[abstract art|abstract]] \"smear paintings.\" His work [[visual]] and [[conceptual art|conceptual]] has been exhibited in New York, Europe and throughout the states.<ref name=\"Smear Painting\">{{cite web |publisher=Redding News Review|title=Smear Painting|url=http://www.reddingnewsreview.com/smearsite/these_are_pictures_of_redding_EU.htm}}</ref>\n\nRedding has been noted for his \"trademark\" style upon his arrival in New York City by NY Art Beat.<ref name=\"NYArtBeat\">{{cite web |publisher=NY Art Beat|title=Rob Redding \"Artist Run\"|url=http://www.nyartbeat.com/event/2017/CF79}}</ref>\n\nIn the fall of 2018, he held his controversial \"BIG BLACK \u0336C\u0336O\u0336C\u0336K\u0336 CANVAS: SIZE matters \u2013 in ART!\"\" solo show at NoHo M55 Gallery. Redding said conceptual \"themes of size as it relates to race are so important in the LGBTQ+ and straight communities, just as size and the debate around blackness - in use of color and participation by people of color - are important in the artistic community. This show unapologetically tackles those themes.\"<ref name=\"NYArtBeat2\">{{cite web |publisher=NY Art Beat2|title=Rob Redding \"BBC\"|url=http://www.nyartbeat.com/event/2018/9329}}</ref> NYC art critic Per Larson, who in the past has compared Redding's work to James Baldwin and called his art \"iconic\", agreed saying viewers of his \"BIG BLACK \u0336C\u0336O\u0336C\u0336K\u0336 CANVAS: SIZE matters \u2013 in ART!\" show will be overwhelmed with \"technical wizardry to grab his interest, and meander around within the square without time, and without a mind to get in the way. Viewing at last with his gut.\"... \"It's pure [[Warhol]] and Maplethorp.\" <ref name=\"PeronArt\">{{cite web |publisher=PeronArt|title=Found: One artist who lives art\u2026|url=https://peronart.com/2017/07/22/found-one-artist-who-lives-art/|date=2017-07-22}}</ref><ref name=\"One Art Space\">{{cite web |publisher=NY Art Beat|title=\"OUTlines\" Exhibition - New York Art Beat|url=http://www.nyartbeat.com/event/2019/2D23}}</ref>\n\nArt Slant wrote that Redding's BBC show \"uses paintings 'Up/Circle Jerk', 'fissure' and 'cock' to spur needed dialog about the familiar black male trope.\" <ref name=\"Art Slant\">{{cite web |publisher=Art Slant|title=BBC- SIZE matters - in ART!|url=https://www.artslant.com/ny/events/show/476277-bbc--size-matters---in-art?tab=EVENT}}</ref> Black Star News wrote of the BBC show: \"Constructivist Expressionist painter Redding breaths new life into geometric shape with radical reductive smearing of thrown pain.\" <ref name=\"Black Star News\">{{cite web |publisher=Black Star News|title= EXHIBITION: BIG BLACK \u0336C\u0336O\u0336C\u0336K\u0336 CANVAS: SIZE MATTERS - IN ART!|url=http://www.blackstarnews.com/entertainment/others/exhibition-big-black-%CC%B6c%CC%B6o%CC%B6c%CC%B6k%CC%B6-canvas-size-matters-in-art.html}}</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 2018, he played with conceptual themes when he wrote the introduction, which was edited by fellow artist Nicolette Reim, for the \"RISE 2018\" art show at NoHo M55 Gallery show. \u201cIt means, to emerge \u2014 artists in this show are surfacing through political and nonpolitical concepts on canvas, paper, other  platforms. \u2018Rise\u2019 is the orbiting of the sun or moon. \u2018Rise\u2019 is the ocean reclaiming the land each evening or how ash from fire darkens the sky. Or how children grow like corn. Or rents double in Dumbo. President Trump's political \u2018rise\u2019 and the fear or favor people may have with his ascension. \u2018Rise\u2019 means to emerge, not always from or for something beautiful.  Rise befits attention \u2014 always.\u201d <ref name=\"BlouinArtInfo\">{{cite web |publisher=BlouinArtInfo|title= Rise | url=https://www.blouinartinfo.com/news/story/3180115/rise-2018-at-noho-m55-gallery-new-york}}</ref>\n\nWhile in Washington, D.C., The Georgetowner highlighted only his art in a group show on Capitol Hill in 2006 writing: \"It is always an event anytime Rob Redding's smear paintings are featured.\" <ref name=\"Georgetowner\">{{cite web |publisher=Georgetowner|title= Review |url=http://www.reddingnewsreview.com/smearsite/Articles/Georgtowner.pdf}}</ref>\n\nRedding also curates shows all over New York. His more than 30 artists art show \"OUTlines\" commemorated 50 years of Pride at One Art Space. Downtown NY said the show \"nailed\" commodification of queerness and New York Art Beat said that show was a \"shaking up the commodification of the LGBTQ+ community.\"<ref name=\"Art Stars Target Commodification\">{{cite web |publisher=DowntownNY|title=Art Stars Target Commodification of Queerness\u00a0|url=\nhttps://www.downtownny.com/events/outlines-art-show-aims-to-target-commodification-of-queerness}}</ref><ref name=\"One Art Space\" />\n\n==Controversy==\nIn May 2011, Redding got into a verbal altercation with talk icon [[Rush Limbaugh]] when he asked [[Michael]] Steele, the former chairman of the Republican National Committee, about a skit in which a Limbaugh staffer \u201creintepreted\u201d his criticism of Pres. Obama's immigration speech in Ebonics.  \u201cI thought it was highly inappropriate,\u201d Steele told Redding. \u201cIt is stupid. It\u2019s not something that furthers the conversation.\u201d Limbaugh responded: \"In what may be a first, we have a formal complaint lodged against the Official Obama Criticizer, Bo Snerdley. Bo Snerdley was recently utilized on this program last week as the Official Obama Criticizer, and it was as though it had happened for the first time. Now, we\u2019ve been featuring the Official Obama Criticizer for close to a year, if not more on this program, but something about last week\u2019s version of the Official Obama Criticizer has rubbed \u2018em wrong out there, particularly your translation for brothers and sisters in the hood. The complaint is that there aren\u2019t any of those listening to the program. Of course, the left and the media are on this kick now that there\u2019s racism everywhere, and really racism and race-baiting has its home on the left. But there\u2019s a show out there called Redding News Review.\"It\u2019s some guy named Rob Redding and his program is syndicated. Whose isn\u2019t? And Rob Redding interviewed the former chairman of the Republican National Committee, Michael Steele. And Redding says, \u201cOkay, Rush Limbaugh is widely thought to be a racist.\u201d No, accused, baselessly so by members of the left when they can't come up with anything better to criticize me for. But nevertheless, 'Rush Limbaugh is widely thought to be a racist.\"<ref name=\"AJC 2\">{{cite web|publisher=AJC |title=WAOK's Rob Redding gets Rush Limbaugh's attention |url=http://blogs.ajc.com/radio-tv-talk/2011/05/20/waoks-rob-redding-gets-rush-limbaughs-attention/ |accessdate=November 18, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120127103157/http://blogs.ajc.com/radio-tv-talk/2011/05/20/waoks-rob-redding-gets-rush-limbaughs-attention/ |archivedate=January 27, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nOn Feb. 6, 2003, Redding's producer Quiana Knox was mysteriously shot at her home in Atlanta Georgia following the show. The murder is still unsolved. On the fifth anniversary of her death he said: \"I can't help but think this crime may have been solved by now if Quiana had been white. Let\u2019s look at the facts: Black victims are all too often overlooked by my friends in the media and police departments across America when we are shot, killed or come up missing. We see the priority that is placed on the lives of whites by looking at the cases of Meredith Emerson and many others. It is time to solve Quiana's case and all the other cases where blacks have been repeatedly ignored.\"<ref name=\"AAnews\">{{cite web |publisher=AllAccess|title=Radio Producer's Murder Still Unsolved After 5 Years|url=http://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/35796/radio-producer-s-murder-still-unsolved-after-5-yea|accessdate=October 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Other work==\nIn spring of 2012, [[Stanford University]] selected him as John S. Knight Journalism Fellowship Semifinalist for his journalism innovation.<ref name=\"Rob Redding bio\">{{cite web |publisher=Redding News Review|title=Redding bio|url=http://www.reddingnewsreview.com/robertreddingsite/biography.html |accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref>\n\nNovember 2009, he founded Black Talkers, a web site which covers the black talk media industry.\n\nThe same year, Redding also narrated  \"Stay Brady Stay,\" a documentary about the future of Louisiana.<ref name=\"RNR2\">{{cite web |publisher=Redding News Review|title=Redding narrates 'Stay Brady Stay'|url=http://reddingnewsreview.com/newspages/2009newspages/redding_narrates_09_091000274.htm |accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://robertredding.com/ Rob Redding official website]\n* [http://reddingnewsreview.com/ ''Redding News Review'' website]\n* [http://smearpainting.com/ Rob Redding art site]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Redding, Rob}}\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n[[Category:African-American television personalities]]\n[[Category:African-American radio personalities]]\n[[Category:American male artists]]\n[[Category:American conceptual artists]]\n[[Category:American sound artists]]\n[[Category:American performance artists]]\n[[Category:American infotainers]]\n[[Category:American male journalists]]\n[[Category:American online publication editors]]\n[[Category:American political commentators]]\n[[Category:American political writers]]\n[[Category:American talk radio hosts]]\n[[Category:American television talk show hosts]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n[[Category:The Washington Times people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox writer\n| name         = Robert \"Rob\" Redding Jr.\n| image        = Rob Redding.jpg\n| imagesize    = \n| caption      = \n| pseudonym    = Rob Redding\n| birth_name   = Robert Redding, Jr.\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1976|01|13}}\n| birth_place  = [[Atlanta]] [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], U.S.\n| death_date   = \n| death_place  =  \n| genre        = Media, music and art\n| subject      = \n| movement     = Independent\n| notableworks = Redding News Review, Author of Why Black Lives Matter, Not a Nonviolent Negro, Disrupter, Where's the Change?, Resurrection and Resolution of Risk\n| occupation   = \n*Chairman and CEO of Redding Communications, Inc.\n*Editor, Publisher and Host of ''[[Redding News Review]]'' \n| years_active = 1994\u2013present \n| alma_mater   = [[Marshall University]] and [[University of Louisiana at Monroe|University of Louisiana]]\n| spouse       = LaWanda Hunt (1999 to 2005, div.)\n| partner      = \n| children     = Rachel Redding (stepdaughter)\n| awards       = 100 Most Important Talk Show Hosts in America, Associated Press award, gold ADDY award\n| website      = \n}}\n'''Robert \"Rob\" Redding, Jr.''' (born January 13, 1976) is an American [[artist]]. His practice spans a broad range of media including sound, performance, [[Conceptual art|conceptual]], language and visual. He is a [[professor]], [[media proprietor]], award-winning [[radio host|radio talk show host]], bestselling [[author]] and [[Independent (voter)|independent]] [[journalist]].<ref name=\"Urbaninsight\">{{cite web |work=Urbaninsight|url=https://www.urbaninsite.com/news/rob-redding-next-thursday/ |title=Biography |accessdate=}}</ref> Redding is known as the founder and [[publisher]] of ''[[Redding News Review]]'' and host of a [[talk radio]] show and [[podcast]]. In 2003, he was among few blacks to be named to Talkers Magazine's \"100 Most Important Radio Talk Show Hosts in America\" and has received a proclamation for his work by the Atlanta City Council the same year.<ref name=\"RNR returns to Atlanta\">{{cite web |work=Redding News Review back in ATL |url=http://www.radiofacts.com/rob-redding-returns-to-waok-in-atlanta/ |title=Biography |accessdate=}}</ref> He made history being the only black program director in white-dominated talk radio station in 2009.<ref name=\"Rob Redding PD\">{{cite web |work=Rob Redding PD |url=http://www.allaccess.com/news-talk-sports/10-questions/archive/4766/10-questions-with-robert-rob-redding-jr |title=10 Questions |accessdate=}}</ref> His web site [[Redding News Review]] has earned three consecutive Black Web Awards.<ref name=\"RNR BWA\">{{cite web |work=Redding News Review BWA |url=http://www2.cincinnati.com/blogs/tv/2011/11/08/rob-redding-show-coming-to-wdbz-am/ |title=Biography |accessdate=}}</ref> He currently runs the web's oldest black news aggregation outlet and first and most successful stand-alone subscriber-based web site and talk show.<ref name=\"RNR sub\">{{cite web |work=Redding News Review Sub |url=http://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/128398/redding-news-review-moves-to-subscription-model |title=Biography |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nRedding is the son of Rev. Robert Redding Sr., a former  Atlanta pastor and former president of the Fayette County's Black Voters League, and the late Mary Ann Redding, who was an Atlanta public school teacher and a Fayette school board candidate.<ref name=\"Redding Artist Statement\">{{cite web |work=Redding News Review |url=http://reddingnewsreview.com/smearsite/robert_redding_jr_art_resume.htm |title=Biography |accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref>\n\nHe gained his artistic ability from his mother Mary - who was part eastern European [[Jewish]], black, white, Native American and Asian - and his abilities to communicate effectively from his mother and father - who is part black and white.<ref name=\"Gay Letter\">{{cite web |work=Out Loud|url=http://gayletter.com/event/rob-redding-on-race-losing-his-boyfriend-to-gun-violence |title=Out Loud Biography }}</ref> And credits his oldest sister Keena for taking him to many of his early art shows and childhood teacher for her influence.<ref name=\"Smear Painting Bio\">{{cite web |work=Smear Painting|url=http://smearpainting.com/robertreddingsite/biography.html |title=Biography |accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref>\n\nHis formal training is in [[Broadcast media|media]]. He graduated from [[Marshall University]] in [[West Virginia]] with a Master's in Communication and is known for his work in sound.<ref name=\"RNR\">{{cite web |work=Redding News Review |url=http://reddingnewsreview.com/robertreddingsite/biography.html |title=Biography |accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Sound==\nHe began his [[performative]] [[Broadcast media|media]] career as a hip-hop radio personality at KZWA-FM, while at [[McNeese State University]] in Lake Charles in 1994.<ref name=\"RNR\">{{cite web |work=Redding News Review |url=http://reddingnewsreview.com/robertreddingsite/biography.html |title=Biography |accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 1996, he accepted a full-time position as a hip-hop night personality at [[WIBB-FM]] in [[Macon, GA]], where he was named \"Tony Smoove\" by his program director. Macon was also the home of another Redding family member, '60s soul singer [[Otis Redding]].<ref name=\"RNR\"/>\n\nHe left hip-hop for talk radio and journalism, working at a series of newspapers: ''The Prince George's Sentinel'', ''The Prince George's Gazette'', ''The Prince George's Journal'', ''The Macon Telegraph'', and finally ''[[The Washington Times]]''. During that same time he began his talk radio career filling in for Bernie McCain on Radio-One's [[WOL (AM)|WOL]] in Washington, D.C. in 1999. In 2001, he landed his first full-time job in talk radio doing afternoons at CBS Radio's [[WAOK]]-AM, where he started ReddingNewsReview.com. He left the station in 2003 and began syndicating his talk radio show while filling in for [[Ambrose I. Lane Sr.]] on SiriusXM 128 [[The Power (XM)|The Power]].<ref name=\"RNR\"/>\n\nHe later inked his own weekend syndication deals with GCN and Sirius XM in 2008, while finishing his undergraduate studies at the University of Louisiana-Monroe.<ref name=\"XM\">{{cite press release |url=http://xmradio.mediaroom.com/index.php?s=press_releases&item=1600 |publisher=XM Radio |title=Press Release}}</ref><ref name=\"ULM\">{{cite press release |url=http://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:SbIogUsUuCsJ:www.ulm.edu/alumni/goodnews/july2009/alumni_news.html+&cd=7&hl=en&ct=clnk&gl=us |publisher=ULM |title=Press Release}}</ref>\n\nOn August 30, 2010, he began doing a weekday show for GCN, while still doing the Sunday show. The weekday show aired in multiple markets and at one time on Sirius XM daily from April 2012 to February 2013. The Sirius XM deal ended after nearly half a decade and more than 420 episodes on Feb. 10, 2013.<ref name=\"Radio Online\">{{cite news |work=Radio Online |title=Rob Redding Launches Syndicated Weekday Show |url=http://news.radio-online.com/cgi-bin/rol.exe/headline_id=n21094 |date=August 19, 2010 |accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"prnewswire\">{{cite news |work=Radio Online |title=SiriusXM Launches \"The B. Smith and 'Thank You Dan' Show\"}}</ref>\n\nRedding moved to Brussels Belgium in 2013. Living in [[Brussels]] communities of [[Saint-Gilles, Belgium]] and then [[Schaerbeek]], he became first to broadcast his afternoon talk show via GCN to American audiences nightly from Europe.<ref name=\"AA\">{{cite web |work=AA |url=http://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/121530/redding-news-review-now-airing-from-brussels |title=news |accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref>\n\nRedding made talk history when he made his program the first ever and most successful stand-alone spoken word program available exclusively to subscribers on his subscriber-supported Web site, at the conclusion of the GCN deal on April 1, 2014.<ref name=\"AA2\">{{cite web |work=AA2 |url=http://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/128398/redding-news-review-moves-to-subscription-model |title=news |accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref> The program celebrated its 1000 episode in June 2018.<ref name=\"Redding 1000\">{{cite web |work=RNR10002 |url=https://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/177266 | title='Redding News Review Unrestricted' Reaches 1,000-Episode Milestone}}</ref><ref name=\"Redding celebrates 1000\">{{cite web |url=http://www.urbaninsite.com/news/rob-redding-celebrates-episode-1000-episode/ | title=Rob Redding Celebrates Episode 1000}}</ref><ref name=\"\u2018Redding Milestone\">{{cite web |work=RNR10004 |url=https://radiofacts.com/redding-news-review-unrestriced/?singlepage=1 | title='Redding News Review Unrestricted' Reaches 1,000-Episode Milestone}}</ref> Radio online said that the show has an \"impressive base\" of nearly half the country listening as it completed its 1000 show.<ref name=\"Episode 1000\">{{cite web |work=Episode 1000 |url=https://news.radio-online.com/cgi-bin/rol.exe/headline_id=n35565 |title=Redding News Review Unrestricted' Reaches 1000th Episode}}</ref>\n\nRedding has also used numerous conceptual elements of sound in his talk shows and inserted his performance into popular culture through music.\n\n* \u201cNot a Nonviolent Negro\u201d(Amazon/CD Baby/Crystal Castle, 2013) \nOn March 5, 2013, he released a [[performative]] [[dance]] [[album]] entitled \"Not a Nonviolent Negro\" on iTunes and Amazon.com via CD Baby. The album, which takes [[sound]] of himself, callers and clips of his talk show and sets them to heavy dance beats, reached No. 1 on Amazon.com. The album is considered a soundtrack to his No. 1 best-selling book \"Not a Nonviolent Negro: How I Survived Obama.\" The book and album were released on the same day.<ref name=\"'Not a Nonviolent Negro' album, book No. 1 in multiple categories\" />\n\n* \u201cUnleash the Whip\u201d(Amazon/CD Baby/Crystal Castle, 2012) \nOn Dec. 4, 2012, he released a performative dance album entitled \"Unleash the Whip!\" on iTunes and Amazon.com via CD Baby. The album, which also takes portions of his talk show and sets them to heavy dance beats, reached No. 2 on Amazon.com and got 3 1/2 stars from former About.com dance music critic Jimi Bruce.<ref name=\"Unleash the Whip! No. 2 on Amazon.com; Gets 3 1/2 stars from About.com's former critic\">{{cite web |title=Unleash the Whip! No. 2 on Amazon.com; Gets 3 1/2 stars from About.com's former critic|url=http://www.reddingnewsreview.com/newspages/2012newspages/unleash_no35_amazon_12_1000121.htm/|accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref>\n\n* \u201cTony Smoove's Aircheck Vol. 1\u201d(Crystal Castle, 1998) \nUnleash the Whip! was his second album. His first album, published under DJ Tony Smoove, did not chart but was the first recording of rapper Bubba Sparxx.<ref name=\"WAOK\u2019s Rob Redding tries his hand in dance music: \u2018Unleash the Whip\u2019\">{{cite web |title=WAOK's Rob Redding tries his hand in dance music: 'Unleash the Whip'|url=http://blogs.ajc.com/radio-tv-talk/2012/10/27/waoks-rob-redding-tries-his-hand-ini-dance-music-unleash-the-whip/|accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=2 style=\"width:13em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=2 style=\"width:13em;\"| Album details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=10| Peak chart positions\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Amazon.com]]<br><ref name=uk>{{cite web|url=http://www.reddingnewsreview.com/newspages/2012newspages/unleash_no35_amazon_12_1000121.htm |title=Amazon.com Charts > Rob Redding|publisher=Redding NewsReview.com|work=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=2012-12-21}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Not a Nonviolent Negro''\n|\n* Released: 5 March 2013\n* Label: Crystal Castle\n* Formats: [[Music download|digital download]]\n| 1 || 1 |\n|-\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Unleash the Whip!''\n|\n* Released: 4 December 2012\n* Label: Crystal Castle\n* Formats: [[Music download|digital download]]\n| 2 || 2 |\n|-\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''Tony Smoove's Aircheck Volume 1''\n|\n* Released: 1998\n* Label: Crystal Castle/Rude Records\n* Format: [[Compact Disc|CD]]\n| - || - |\n|-\n|}\n\n==Language Arts and Sound ==\nRedding's Web site and talk show, which are both called ''[[Redding News Review]]'', are avant-garde creations.<ref name=\"AllAccess\">{{cite web |url=http://www.allaccess.com/news-talk-sports/10-questions/archive/4766-10-questions-with-robert-rob-redding-jr |title=10 questions with.... Robert \"Rob\" Redding Jr. |work=Redding News Review |accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref> The Web site has been called the \"vanguard of Internet news sites\" by AllAccess.com.<ref name=\"AllAccess\">{{cite web |url=http://www.allaccess.com/news-talk-sports/10-questions/archive/4766-10-questions-with-robert-rob-redding-jr |title=10 questions with.... Robert \"Rob\" Redding Jr. |work=Redding News Review |accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref> The Web site has been called \"an Internet clearinghouse for African-American news,\" by The Atlanta Journal-Constitution.<ref name=\"AJC\"/>\n\nThe Web site - which is the first subscriber supported and oldest black news aggregation portal - stories are syndicated hourly by Google News. Its stories have been heard regularly on [[NPR]] and the [[Fox News Channel]]. Its comprehensive coverage of the black community became a resource for Fox News during the [[Don Imus]]' [[Don Imus#Rutgers women's basketball controversy|\"nappy-headed ho's\" controversy]]. Its scoops have also been acknowledged or linked to by [[Black Entertainment Television|BET]], [[MSNBC]], ''[[The Hill (newspaper)|The Hill]]'', ''[[Roll Call]]'', ''[[The Baltimore Sun]]'', ''[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]'', ''[[The Washington Post]]'',''[[The Washington Times]]'', and The [[National Newspaper Association]].<ref name=\"reddingnews\"/>\n\nRedding News Review exposed former Atlanta Mayor and United Nations Ambassador [[Andrew Young]]'s comments about Sen. [[Barack Obama]] not being ready to be president.<ref name=\"AJC\">{{cite news |first=Jim |last=Galloway |work=Political Insider |publisher=[[Atlanta Journal-Constitution]] |title=On how Andy Young\u2019s comments on Obama came to light |url=http://www.ajc.com/metro/content/shared-blogs/ajc/politicalinsider/entries/2007/12/10/more_on_those_obama_comments_b.html |date=December 10, 2007 |accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe Web site exposed that syndicated columnist [[Leonard Pitts]] was being threatened by a white supremacist group.<ref name=\"reddingnews\">{{cite web |url=http://reddingnewsreview.com/ourstory.htm |title=Our Story |work=Redding News Review |accessdate=November 18, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111027231808/http://reddingnewsreview.com/ourstory.htm |archivedate=October 27, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nThe Web site exposed NBC Nightly News Managing Editor and Anchor [[Brian Williams]] comments about diversity not being a big issue. Both Williams and NBC apologized for those comments.<ref name=\"reddingnews\"/>\n\nOn the radio talk show Redding, who refers to himself as \"America's Independent Voice\", has been called \"The voice of the voiceless\" and \"the prophet of rage\" by his listeners.<ref name=\"reddingnews\"/>\n\nRedding News Review has been the most listened to black independent talk show host in the United States of America&nbsp;\u2013 heard six days a week for nearly half decade and more than 420 episodes in all 50 states via Sirius XM Satellite Radio and on numerous radio stations for more than 6 years and 3,600 hours via his former network deal with Genesis Communications Network.<ref name=\"reddingnews\"/><ref name=\"radiofacts2\">{{cite web |url=http://www.radiofacts.com/rob-redding-returns-to-waok-in-atlanta/ |title=Rob Redding Returns to WAOK in Atlanta |work=Radio Facts |accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe Redding New Review radio show host Rob Redding was named one of the \"100 most important radio talk show hosts in America\" by industry trade ''Talkers'' magazine.<ref name=\"radiofacts2\"/>\n\nHe has also been called a \"rising star\" (''[[Talkers magazine]]''), \"one of the most respected names in the media\" (''[[Upscale magazine]]''), \"one of the most intellectual and intriguing radio talk show hosts since [[Tavis Smiley]]\" (''[[Radio Facts]]''). The same publication later wrote he is \u201cincredibly intelligent and talented radio talk show host\u2026he is a rolling stone who is not afraid to tackle some of the \u2018uncomfortable\u2019 issues in the black community.\" <ref name=\"Radio Facts 2017\">{{cite web |url=https://radiofacts.com/rob-redding-confronts-caller-about-black-homophobia/ |title=Rob Redding Confronts Caller about Black Homophobia |work=Radio Facts |accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref> He was awarded a proclamation by the [[Atlanta, Georgia#Government|Atlanta City Council]] for his hard hitting uniquely Independent [[talk radio]] show.<ref name=\"GCN\"/>\n\nOn April 1, 2014, Redding's talk show morphed into \"Redding News Review Unrestricted\" becoming the first ever and most successful stand-alone spoken word program available exclusively on a Web site - via ReddingNewsReview.com<ref name=\"GCN\">{{Cite web | url=http://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/128398/redding-news-review-moves-to-subscription-model | title=Redding News Review Moves to Subscription Model}}</ref>\nJust four years later, the program celebrated its 1000 episode in June 2018.<ref name=\"Redding 1000\">{{cite web |work=RNR10002 |url=https://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/177266 | title='Redding News Review Unrestricted' Reaches 1,000-Episode Milestone}}</ref><ref name=\"Redding celebrates 1000\">{{cite web |url=http://www.urbaninsite.com/news/rob-redding-celebrates-episode-1000-episode/ | title=Rob Redding Celebrates Episode 1000}}</ref><ref name=\"\u2018Redding Milestone\">{{cite web |work=RNR10004 |url=https://radiofacts.com/redding-news-review-unrestriced/?singlepage=1 | title='Redding News Review Unrestricted' Reaches 1,000-Episode Milestone}}</ref> Radio online said that the show has an \"impressive base\" of nearly half the country listening as it completed its 1000 show.<ref name=\"Episode 1000\">{{cite web |work=Episode 1000 |url=https://news.radio-online.com/cgi-bin/rol.exe/headline_id=n35565 |title=Redding News Review Unrestricted' Reaches 1000th Episode}}</ref> Castropolis said Redding's show is \"one of the most important Black Voices in America today.\" <ref name=\"Castropolis Instagram\">{{cite web |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B4YF_Vgp-8W/ |title=Rob Redding on Instagram |work=Insta |accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to being on the air nationwide, he was once one of the only black program directors of a mainstream conservative [[talk radio]] station, [[KMLB]]-AM in [[Monroe, Louisiana]].<ref name=\"Radio Ink\">https://docs.google.com/gview?a=v&q=cache%3A9mM2cMXpkkAJ%3Awww.reddingnewsreview.com%2Fpdfs%2FRI_p13_Redding_10-19_p37.PDF+kmlb+redding&hl=en&gl=us&sig=AFQjCNFPJ8xj4bI6LwZhdrxq9TqEbeqLnw&pli=1 Rob Redding, KMLB</ref>\n\n==Best-Selling Language Arts Publications==\nIn language arts, Redding is author of nine consecutive best-selling [[books]] and an e-guide.\n\n* \u201cThe Professor\u201d(Amazon, 2019)\nRedding's most recent book, \"The Professor: Witnessing White Power\" released on May 1 uses empiricism to explore how interracial gay encounters may have influenced black leadership. The book details the sex lives of [[Jean-Michel Basquiat]], [[James Baldwin]], [[Marvin Gaye]], [[Richard Pryor]] and [[Malcolm X]]. It contains new information about Basquiat\u2019s relationship with Klaus Nomi. Radio Facts called the book \"hard hitting\", \"controversial\" and \"explosive.\" The book debuted at No. 1 on Amazon's \u201cNew Releases in LGBT Literary Criticism\u201d and \u201cNew Releases in Gay & Lesbian Literary Criticism.\u201d <ref name=\"Radio Facts\">{{cite web |publisher=http://www.radiofacts.com|title=Rob Redding\u2019s book \u2018The Professor\u2019 hits No. 1|url= https://radiofacts.com/rob-reddings-book-the-professor-hits-no-1/}}</ref> The book is his most successful since 2013 \"Not a Nonviolent Negro.\"\n\n* \u201cOut Loud\u201d(Amazon, 2017) \nRedding's Out Loud was his tell-all performance and conceptual autobiography. The [[performative]] Brook - half audio/broadcast and half book - was released on Oct. 13, 2017 exclusively to his talk show subscribers and to the entire nation on Nov. 6th. The Brook has debuted at No. 2 on \"Amazon.com Hot New Releases Gay and Lesbian Biographies and Memoirs.\"  The book matched his most successful books Sinister Citizen and Not a Nonviolent Negro by being ranked in the Top 100 for five straight weeks. The book has been called \"shocking\" by CBS.<ref name=\"CBS\">{{cite web |publisher=www.atlanta.cbslocal.com|title=Black Independent Radio Host Releases Tell All Book That Reveals His Alternative Lifestyle|url= http://atlanta.cbslocal.com/2017/11/24/black-conservative-radio-host-reveals-he-sleeps-with-white-men/|date=2017-11-24}}</ref> The NYC GAYLETTER called the book \"juicy\" just after Redding pulled it from Amazon in January 2018 and making it only available for a short time on his website ReddingNewsReview.com <ref name=\"GayLetter\">{{cite web |publisher=www.gayletter.com|title=Rob Redding|url= http://gayletter.com/event/rob-redding-on-race-losing-his-boyfriend-to-gun-violence/}}</ref><ref name=\"Amazon Image\">{{cite web |publisher=www.Amazon.net|title=Amazon|url= http://reddingnewsreview.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/no2.jpg}}</ref>\n\n* \u201cSinister Citizen\u201d(Amazon, 2017) \nRedding's book, \"Sinister Citizen\" is his first fiction book ever. The book, which deals with President Trump's America, has been called \"fascinating\" by KKXX. The book has reached the Top 30 on \"Amazon.com Hot New Releases LGBT Short Reads\" and was in the Top 50 in pre-orders on the same list.<ref name=\"KKXX intv\">{{cite web |publisher=www.kkxx.net|title=KKXX intv|url= http://www.kkxx.net/all-podcasts/LocalTalk/2017_03_17_Jerry-Olenyn-Sinister-Citizen-Rob-Redding.mp3}}</ref>\n\n* ''Why Black Lives Matter: How Borigination explains how to get police and whites to treat blacks like people'' (Amazon, 2015)\nRedding's conceptual book, ''Why Black Lives Matter: How Borigination explains how to get police and whites to treat blacks like people'' was officially released on July 6, 2015, but peaked at the top of multiple charts on Amazon.com two days ahead that when it was exclusively released to subscribers of his talk show and website on July 3. The book surged to No. 1 on Amazon.com \"Hot New Releases\" in \"Philosophy and Reference\" and \"Philosophy and Criticism\" categories and rose to No. 2  in \"Philosophy and Criticism\" and \"No. 3 in \"Philosophy and Reference\" respectively among Amazon.com's Best Sellers lists. This was also the first time Redding has topped the Amazon.com \"Hot New Releases\" in \"Philosophy and Reference\" list since his 2012 release of his book \"Disrupter.\" The foreword was pinned by Dr. Lewis R. Gordon, who also wrote a foreword for Redding's book \"Resurrection.\" <ref name=\"Radio Vet \">{{cite web |publisher=radiofacts.com|title=Radio Vet Talk Show Host Rob Redding Writes Another Best-Selling Amazon E-Book \"Why Black Lives in Matter\u2026\"|url=http://www.radiofacts.com/radio-vet-talk-show-host-rob-redding-writes-another-best-selling-amazon-e-book-why-black-lives-in-matter/}}</ref><ref name=\"Rob Redding Bio\">{{cite web |publisher=RobRedding.com|title=Rob Redding's Book A Top Seller|url=http://www.reddingnewsreview.com/robertreddingsite/biography.html}}</ref>\n\n* \u201cUnthinkable: Poems, Philosophies and Paintings\u201d(Amazon, 2014) \nRedding's conceptual \"Unthinkable: Poems, Philosophies and Paintings\", released on July 7, 2014, was finished while he lived in [[Brussels]] after more than 20 years of writing and painting. \"Unthinkable\" peaked on July 13, 2014 on Amazon \"Hot New Releases\" at \"No. 4\" in \"Art and Painting\" and \"No. 7\" in \"Reference and Quotations.\" It also ranked \"No. 27\" in \"Art and Painting\" and \"No. 47\" in \"Reference and Quotations\" respectively on Amazon.com's Best Sellers lists.The book was provided for free to subscribers of Redding's talk show and website.<ref name=\"Rob Redding\u2019s Book A Top Seller\">{{cite web |publisher=UrbanInsite|title=Rob Redding's Book A Top Seller|url=http://www.urbaninsite.com/?p=34461}}</ref>\n\n* \u201cNot a Nonviolent Negro: How I Survived Obama\u201d(Amazon, 2013) \nRedding's most successful conceptual book, \"Not a Nonviolent Negro: How I Survived Obama\" debuted at No. 1 on Amazon.com in three categories on March 6, 2013. The book, which was released on March 5, was on No. 1 \"Best Sellers List\" in \"Nationalism\" and \"Hot New Releases\" in the \"Social Philosophy\" and \"Nationalism\" categories respectfully. He says it is his most successful book to date. The book also has a soundtrack \"Not a Nonviolent Negro\" which also went to No. 1 on Amazon.com.<ref name=\"'Not a Nonviolent Negro' album, book No. 1 in multiple categories\">{{cite web |publisher=CBS|title=Disrupter|url=http://www.reddingnewsreview.com/newspages/2013newspages/not_a_nonviolent_negro_13_10000023.htm}}</ref>\n\n* \u201cDisrupter: Pathway to Political Independence\u201d(Amazon, 2012) \nHis second best-selling conceptual and [[performance]] book was \"Disrupter: Pathway to Political Independence\". Disrupter debuted at No. 1 on Amazon.com \"Hot New Releases\" - \"Political Reference\" list on Aug. 13 2012 and remained there for more than a week. The book is considered a reference guide for independents and includes parts of Redding's life story.<ref name=\"Disrupter\">{{cite web |publisher=CBS|title=Disrupter|url=http://atlanta.cbslocal.com/2012/08/14/redding-book-debuts-at-1-on-amazon/|accessdate=August 15, 2011}}</ref>\n\n* \u201cResurrection: A Historical Anthology of two Forgotten African-American Philosophers\u201d(Amazon, 2012) \nHis third best-selling book was \"Resurrection: A Historical Anthology of two Forgotten African-American Philosophers.\" The e-book, which was released on April 4, 2012, reached No. 3 on the Amazon.com list of \"Hot New Releases\" in less than a week.<ref name=\"Resurrection\">{{cite web |publisher=Resurrection|title=Resurrection|url=http://www.urbanradionation.com/2012/04/talk-show-host-rob-reddings-new-book-on.html|accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref>\n\n* \u201cWhere's the Change?: Why Neither Obama, nor the GOP Can Solve America\u2019s Problems\u201d(Amazon, 2012)\nRedding's conceptual e-book \"Where's the Change?: Why Neither Obama, nor the GOP Can Solve America\u2019s Problems'', which was released on Jan. 13, 2012, reached the top 50 on Amazon.com. The book quickly has been as high as No. 30 on Amazon's Top 100 books. Redding is also author of ''Hired Hatred: Why politicians and the political prejudices they tout are mutually exclusive from good government''. His Independent [[manifesto]] is said to \"invoke an activist spirit,\" according to a review in 2005 by New York's ''Black Star News''.<ref name=\"Where's the Change?\">{{cite web |publisher=Where's the Change?|title=Where's the Change|url=http://atlanta.cbslocal.com/2012/02/01/wheres-the-change-hits-top-50-on-amazon-com|accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref>\n\n* \u201cOne a Day Fade Away\u201d(Amazon, 2012)\nHe is also the author of the \u201cOne a Day Fade Away\u201d diet e-guide, which was ranked as high as No. 29 on the \u201cAmazon Best Sellers\u201d listing in April 2012. The guide has been out since 2011 and was his third best-seller in less than 90 days.<ref name=\"One a Day Fade Away\">{{cite web |publisher=One a Day Fade Away|title=One a Day Fade Away |url=http://urbanradionation.wordpress.com/2012/04/27/rob-redding-has-third-best-selling-book-in-90-days}}</ref>\n\n==Academic Language Arts Publications==\n* \u201cBlack Voices, White Power: Members of the black press make meaning of media hegemony\u201d(Journal of Black Studies, 2017) \nIn winter of 2015, he wrote his [[thesis]] \u201cBlack Voices, White Power: Members of the black press make meaning of media hegemony\u201d to satisfy his Master's in [[Communication Studies]] degree while teaching at [[Marshall University]]. He said that the thesis \"gives an on the record voice to black employees who toil at white-owned black-focused media about their experiences as it relates to content decisions and beyond.\u201d The thesis was published in the Journal of Black Studies in March 2017.<ref name=\"Rob Redding JOBS\">{{cite journal |title=Rob Redding thesis |journal=Journal of Black Studies |volume = 48|issue=2 |pages=143\u2013164 |doi=10.1177/0021934716681152 |year=2017 |last1=Redding |first1=Robert }}</ref><ref name=\"Rob Redding Masters\">{{cite web |publisher=Redding News Review|title=Rob Redding Responds To \"You Tell Us\" Urban Radio The Future|url=http://www.urbaninsite.com/voice/insite/rob-redding-responds-to-you-tell-us-urban-radio-the-future/ |accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref>\n\n* \u201cResolution of Risk\u201d(The Journal of the International Public Debate Association, 2009)\nRedding is also author of the \"Resolution of Risk,\" which was first used at the International Public Debate Association's National Tournament after being published in the organization's peer-reviewed publication, \"The Journal of the International Public Debate Association,\" and being presented by Redding before a packed audience.<ref name=\"Resolution of Risk\">{{cite press release |first=Laura |last=Harris |publisher=[[University of Louisiana at Monroe]], Office of Public Information |title=Redding's article published in peer-reviewed journal |url=http://www.ulm.edu/universityrelations/news/apr09/redding.html |date=April 16, 2009 |accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Visual and Conceptual Art==\nRedding is an [[artist]], who paints [[abstract art|abstract]] \"smear paintings.\" His work [[visual]] and [[conceptual art|conceptual]] has been exhibited in New York, Europe and throughout the states.<ref name=\"Smear Painting\">{{cite web |publisher=Redding News Review|title=Smear Painting|url=http://www.reddingnewsreview.com/smearsite/these_are_pictures_of_redding_EU.htm}}</ref>\n\nRedding has been noted for his \"trademark\" style upon his arrival in New York City by NY Art Beat.<ref name=\"NYArtBeat\">{{cite web |publisher=NY Art Beat|title=Rob Redding \"Artist Run\"|url=http://www.nyartbeat.com/event/2017/CF79}}</ref>\n\nIn the fall of 2018, he held his controversial \"BIG BLACK \u0336C\u0336O\u0336C\u0336K\u0336 CANVAS: SIZE matters \u2013 in ART!\"\" solo show at NoHo M55 Gallery. Redding said conceptual \"themes of size as it relates to race are so important in the LGBTQ+ and straight communities, just as size and the debate around blackness - in use of color and participation by people of color - are important in the artistic community. This show unapologetically tackles those themes.\"<ref name=\"NYArtBeat2\">{{cite web |publisher=NY Art Beat2|title=Rob Redding \"BBC\"|url=http://www.nyartbeat.com/event/2018/9329}}</ref> NYC art critic Per Larson, who in the past has compared Redding's work to James Baldwin and called his art \"iconic\", agreed saying viewers of his \"BIG BLACK \u0336C\u0336O\u0336C\u0336K\u0336 CANVAS: SIZE matters \u2013 in ART!\" show will be overwhelmed with \"technical wizardry to grab his interest, and meander around within the square without time, and without a mind to get in the way. Viewing at last with his gut.\"... \"It's pure [[Warhol]] and Maplethorp.\" <ref name=\"PeronArt\">{{cite web |publisher=PeronArt|title=Found: One artist who lives art\u2026|url=https://peronart.com/2017/07/22/found-one-artist-who-lives-art/|date=2017-07-22}}</ref><ref name=\"One Art Space\">{{cite web |publisher=NY Art Beat|title=\"OUTlines\" Exhibition - New York Art Beat|url=http://www.nyartbeat.com/event/2019/2D23}}</ref>\n\nArt Slant wrote that Redding's BBC show \"uses paintings 'Up/Circle Jerk', 'fissure' and 'cock' to spur needed dialog about the familiar black male trope.\" <ref name=\"Art Slant\">{{cite web |publisher=Art Slant|title=BBC- SIZE matters - in ART!|url=https://www.artslant.com/ny/events/show/476277-bbc--size-matters---in-art?tab=EVENT}}</ref> Black Star News wrote of the BBC show: \"Constructivist Expressionist painter Redding breaths new life into geometric shape with radical reductive smearing of thrown pain.\" <ref name=\"Black Star News\">{{cite web |publisher=Black Star News|title= EXHIBITION: BIG BLACK \u0336C\u0336O\u0336C\u0336K\u0336 CANVAS: SIZE MATTERS - IN ART!|url=http://www.blackstarnews.com/entertainment/others/exhibition-big-black-%CC%B6c%CC%B6o%CC%B6c%CC%B6k%CC%B6-canvas-size-matters-in-art.html}}</ref>\n\nIn the summer of 2018, he played with conceptual themes when he wrote the introduction, which was edited by fellow artist Nicolette Reim, for the \"RISE 2018\" art show at NoHo M55 Gallery show. \u201cIt means, to emerge \u2014 artists in this show are surfacing through political and nonpolitical concepts on canvas, paper, other  platforms. \u2018Rise\u2019 is the orbiting of the sun or moon. \u2018Rise\u2019 is the ocean reclaiming the land each evening or how ash from fire darkens the sky. Or how children grow like corn. Or rents double in Dumbo. President Trump's political \u2018rise\u2019 and the fear or favor people may have with his ascension. \u2018Rise\u2019 means to emerge, not always from or for something beautiful.  Rise befits attention \u2014 always.\u201d <ref name=\"BlouinArtInfo\">{{cite web |publisher=BlouinArtInfo|title= Rise | url=https://www.blouinartinfo.com/news/story/3180115/rise-2018-at-noho-m55-gallery-new-york}}</ref>\n\nWhile in Washington, D.C., The Georgetowner highlighted only his art in a group show on Capitol Hill in 2006 writing: \"It is always an event anytime Rob Redding's smear paintings are featured.\" <ref name=\"Georgetowner\">{{cite web |publisher=Georgetowner|title= Review |url=http://www.reddingnewsreview.com/smearsite/Articles/Georgtowner.pdf}}</ref>\n\nRedding also curates shows all over New York. His more than 30 artists art show \"OUTlines\" commemorated 50 years of Pride at One Art Space. Downtown NY said the show \"nailed\" commodification of queerness and New York Art Beat said that show was a \"shaking up the commodification of the LGBTQ+ community.\"<ref name=\"Art Stars Target Commodification\">{{cite web |publisher=DowntownNY|title=Art Stars Target Commodification of Queerness\u00a0|url=\nhttps://www.downtownny.com/events/outlines-art-show-aims-to-target-commodification-of-queerness}}</ref><ref name=\"One Art Space\" />\n\n==Controversy==\nIn May 2011, Redding got into a verbal altercation with talk icon [[Rush Limbaugh]] when he asked [[Michael]] Steele, the former chairman of the Republican National Committee, about a skit in which a Limbaugh staffer \u201creintepreted\u201d his criticism of Pres. Obama's immigration speech in Ebonics.  \u201cI thought it was highly inappropriate,\u201d Steele told Redding. \u201cIt is stupid. It\u2019s not something that furthers the conversation.\u201d Limbaugh responded: \"In what may be a first, we have a formal complaint lodged against the Official Obama Criticizer, Bo Snerdley. Bo Snerdley was recently utilized on this program last week as the Official Obama Criticizer, and it was as though it had happened for the first time. Now, we\u2019ve been featuring the Official Obama Criticizer for close to a year, if not more on this program, but something about last week\u2019s version of the Official Obama Criticizer has rubbed \u2018em wrong out there, particularly your translation for brothers and sisters in the hood. The complaint is that there aren\u2019t any of those listening to the program. Of course, the left and the media are on this kick now that there\u2019s racism everywhere, and really racism and race-baiting has its home on the left. But there\u2019s a show out there called Redding News Review.\"It\u2019s some guy named Rob Redding and his program is syndicated. Whose isn\u2019t? And Rob Redding interviewed the former chairman of the Republican National Committee, Michael Steele. And Redding says, \u201cOkay, Rush Limbaugh is widely thought to be a racist.\u201d No, accused, baselessly so by members of the left when they can't come up with anything better to criticize me for. But nevertheless, 'Rush Limbaugh is widely thought to be a racist.\"<ref name=\"AJC 2\">{{cite web|publisher=AJC |title=WAOK's Rob Redding gets Rush Limbaugh's attention |url=http://blogs.ajc.com/radio-tv-talk/2011/05/20/waoks-rob-redding-gets-rush-limbaughs-attention/ |accessdate=November 18, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120127103157/http://blogs.ajc.com/radio-tv-talk/2011/05/20/waoks-rob-redding-gets-rush-limbaughs-attention/ |archivedate=January 27, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nOn Feb. 6, 2003, Redding's producer Quiana Knox was mysteriously shot at her home in Atlanta Georgia following the show. The murder is still unsolved. On the fifth anniversary of her death he said: \"I can't help but think this crime may have been solved by now if Quiana had been white. Let\u2019s look at the facts: Black victims are all too often overlooked by my friends in the media and police departments across America when we are shot, killed or come up missing. We see the priority that is placed on the lives of whites by looking at the cases of Meredith Emerson and many others. It is time to solve Quiana's case and all the other cases where blacks have been repeatedly ignored.\"<ref name=\"AAnews\">{{cite web |publisher=AllAccess|title=Radio Producer's Murder Still Unsolved After 5 Years|url=http://www.allaccess.com/net-news/archive/story/35796/radio-producer-s-murder-still-unsolved-after-5-yea|accessdate=October 8, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Other work==\nIn spring of 2012, [[Stanford University]] selected him as John S. Knight Journalism Fellowship Semifinalist for his journalism innovation.<ref name=\"Rob Redding bio\">{{cite web |publisher=Redding News Review|title=Redding bio|url=http://www.reddingnewsreview.com/robertreddingsite/biography.html |accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref>\n\nNovember 2009, he founded Black Talkers, a web site which covers the black talk media industry.\n\nThe same year, Redding also narrated  \"Stay Brady Stay,\" a documentary about the future of Louisiana.<ref name=\"RNR2\">{{cite web |publisher=Redding News Review|title=Redding narrates 'Stay Brady Stay'|url=http://reddingnewsreview.com/newspages/2009newspages/redding_narrates_09_091000274.htm |accessdate=November 18, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://robertredding.com/ Rob Redding official website]\n* [http://reddingnewsreview.com/ ''Redding News Review'' website]\n* [http://smearpainting.com/ Rob Redding art site]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Redding, Rob}}\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n[[Category:African-American television personalities]]\n[[Category:African-American radio personalities]]\n[[Category:American male artists]]\n[[Category:American conceptual artists]]\n[[Category:American sound artists]]\n[[Category:American performance artists]]\n[[Category:American infotainers]]\n[[Category:American male journalists]]\n[[Category:American online publication editors]]\n[[Category:American political commentators]]\n[[Category:American political writers]]\n[[Category:American talk radio hosts]]\n[[Category:American television talk show hosts]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n[[Category:The Washington Times people]]\n", "name_user": "Quebec99", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixed reference", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rob_Redding"}
{"title_page": "Viivi Puskala", "text_new": "{{short description|Finnish cyclist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = Viivi Puskala\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| fullname       = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1999|1|16|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = \n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| currentteam    = \n| discipline     = \n| role           = Rider\n| ridertype      = \n| amateuryears1  = \n| amateurteam1   = \n| proyears1      = \n| proteam1       = \n| majorwins      = \n| medaltemplates = \n| show-medals    = \n}}\n'''Viivi Puskala''' (born 16 January 1999) is a Finnish [[bicycle racing|racing cyclist]].<ref name=\"Bio\">{{cite web |url=https://www.procyclingstats.com/rider.php?id=188143 |title=Viivi Puskala |work=ProCyclingStats |accessdate=30 September 2018 }}</ref> She rode in the [[2018 UCI Road World Championships \u2013 Women's road race|women's road race]] event at the [[2018 UCI Road World Championships]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.procyclingstats.com/race/world-championship-we/2018/result |title=2018: World Championships - Women's Road Race |work=ProCyclingStats |accessdate=30 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Puskala, Viivi}}\n[[Category:1999 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Finnish female cyclists]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n{{Finland-cycling-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Finnish cyclist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name           = Viivi Puskala\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| fullname       = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1999|1|16|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = \n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| currentteam    = \n| discipline     = \n| role           = Rider\n| ridertype      = \n| amateuryears1  = \n| amateurteam1   = \n| proyears1      = \n| proteam1       = \n| majorwins      = \